column168: On March 4, 2019 at 0352 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal LAB regarding a cargo release. It was reported that during unloading, a forklift punctured (1) 249-pounds helium tank of UN1963, Helium, Refrigerated Liquid, 2.2 "Helium" to the trailer. The terminal requested a contractor to be dispatched. After arriving on site, the contractor stated that the helium container was jostled loose and fell on the floor causing the valve to open and release the contents of the cylinder to the interior of the trailer releasing an unknown amount. The contractor up-righted the cylinder and closed the valve. No waste was generated.

column168: On March 2, 2019 at 0140 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal XIN regarding a cargo release. It was reported that there was a release of UN1268, Petroleum Distellates, N.O.S., 3, PGIII "UN1268 Petroleum Distillates" from (1) 330-gallon metal tote to the trailer floor. The terminal requested a contractor be dispatched. After arriving to the terminal, the contractor confirmed that approximately 5-gallons of product released to a 10' x 3' area of the trailer floor due to one of the ears being pulled back on the cam lock fittings of the valve plug causing the plug to fall out. The tote was re-secured with a rag and stuffed in the valve opening and the plug placed back on with the ears fastened, chem tape was then secured on the valve to secure the plug from falling back out. The contractor applied simple green solution to the trailer floor to eliminate the odor. ERTS then told the terminal that the trailer needed to be aired out longer and washed to further reduce the odor of the chemical. The debris was placed inside (1) 55-gallon metal drum. The drum as well as the metal tote were left on site and staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: At 02:57 EST ERST was contacted by Frank Merchant of XPO that (1) 40lb bag of UN3349, 6.1 Pyrethroid pesticide, solid, toxic spilled due to improper loading. It was reported that 1 40lb bag released to the tail of the trailer. ERTS determined that the hazardous nature of the product was cause for concern. ERTS called dispatched Environmental Works with an ETA of 1030 ET. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident. Contractor confirmed 5 lbs. released from 3 bags. It appeared the damage occurred before loading as there was loose powder within the shrink wrap. The damaged bags and sweepings have been containerized into a 55 gallon DM

column43: Zep Heavy Duty Truck and Trailer Cleaner
column168: At 1800 EST, Tyler Shook with ABF Freight notified ERTS of a cargo release. It was reported that 1-5 gallon poly pail of UN3266 released to the shrink wrap and trailer floor of unit #400810. Mr. Shook advised the trade name is unavailable at this time due to the pails being shrink-wrapped together on the trailer. Mr. Shook requested ERTS coordinate with a network contractor to clean the release. Mr. Shook stated photos of the BOL will be provided to ERTS. 2005 EST, The contractor identified the leaking product to be Zep Heavy Duty Truck and Trailer Cleaner in 5-gallon poly pails. The contractor is restacking the pallet to get to the damaged containers on the bottom. 2100 EST, The contractor has identified 10 pails that were damaged. The contractor suspects that the pallet was wrapped too tightly and the handles dug into the pails and caused the damage to the pails during transit. The contractor is transferring the contents of the damaged pails into one 55 gallon poly drum. 2315 EST, The contractor is complete at this time. The contractor found that Ten 5 gallon pails of UN3266 Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Inorganic, N.O.S. (Sodium Hydroxide) - Trade name: Zep Heavy Duty Truck and Trailer Wash, had released approximately 10 gallons to a 10'x6' area of trailer floor. The contractor consolidated the remaining material into One 55 gallon poly drum and containerized absorbents, impacted debris, and the damaged containers, into One 55 gallon poly drum, One 30 gallon poly drum, and One Cubic Yard Box. The trailer floor was neutralized with a Citric Acid and Water solution. The neutralized material was then collected with absorbents and containerized.

At 1052 ET, Matt with Terminal UDV notified ERTS of a 3 gallon release of UN3109 "Biotrol 150" from a 6 gallon plastic jerry can to trailer 317-5474. It was stated the can does not look to be damaged and it is unclear how the release happened. No soils, drains, or waterways were reported to have been impacted by this release. Contractor verified the container and the product. The container did not appear to have any damage. Contractor placed the jerry can in a (1) 55 gallon poly drum. The released chemical has impacted adjacent packages, including a bag of fertilizer. Contractor spoke with terminal personnel with ERTS on the phone and terminal personnel agreed that the impacted packages are a loss and will need to be containerized. Impacted metal stakes were placed in a 55-gallon drum, stakes had holes in the metal which was saturated with the "Biotrol 150", soda ash was placed in the container in an effort to neutralize the hazardous material. The impacted bad of fertilizer was placed in a 55 gallon poly drum by itself due to the possible reaction the "Biotrol 150" could have with the magnesium in the fertilizer. Soda ash was placed in the drum with the fertilizer bag to minimize possible reaction. The floor dry used by terminal personnel began to react with the "Biotrol 150" causing a thermal reaction, per the SDS the material was placed in a 30-gallon poly drum and diluted with water. The 30 gallon drum also includes the PPE used during the cleanup.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: On 3/6 at 1415 et, Ian Shaw with XPO terminal XCO called ERTS regarding a 1 gallon release of UN3266 corrosive liquid, basic (Nu-Brite) from a box containing 4 - 1 gal jugs in trailer # 3177438. The spill was the result of improper blocking/ bracing by the previous terminal XIN causing a load shift with adjacent freight that punctured the box. No release outside of trailer. EMS confirmed approximately 2 gals of UN3266 "Nu-Brite" impacted a 5 ft x 5 ft area of trailer floor. The impacted trailer floor and pallet were neutralized with citric acid and pH tested to verify. There were 6 impacted boxes which had their contents transferred onto the pallet for salvage and were broken down for waste. All waste was containerized into 55 gal poly drum for waste and staged onsite.  There was some product remaining in the 4 damaged jugs.

column168: On 03/01/2019 at around 2300 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Boyles Yard (Birmingham, AL MP 000389) reported that an employee was exposed due to a product leak from tank car GATX63655, a loaded tank car of Methanol. The car was isolated and the shipper, Stolt-Nielsen, was notified. Marion Environmental Inc (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, responded and found 6 of 6 manway securement bolts to be less than tool tight and visible product that had leaked from the manway onto the sides of the car. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Stolt-Nielsen (Richie Austin 1-713-906-6560).  MEI secured the manway securement bolts and wiped down the outsides of the car.  The employee was treated by EMS and transported to an offsite healthcare facility.  The car was released.    NAR Cause Code: 200 – Manway Hinged/ Bolted – bolts/ nuts less than tool tight  5(5+3+0) x (2+5) = 280 NARRI   Birmingham, AL– 03/01/19 –GATX63655-Methanol

At 1427 on 3-12-2019, the WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector was inspecting an inbound train when he heard a hissing noise coming from the top of car CBTX 784795.  He notified the Brewster Yard Master who then contacted myself, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I investigated and found that the Vapor Valve was leaking at the valve plug.  I tried to close the valve handle to see if the leak would stop and it did.  I checked the valve plug and it was only hand tight. I then tightened the valve plug.  I checked the liquid valves and they were tight along with the valve plugs.  I removed old seal number 4979485 from the protective housing lid and installed new seal number 971770.  I then released the car for service.     NARRI: 5(4+5)x2)+47                                                              Cause Code: 390

column168: On March 4th at 0800 our driver pulled out of the plant on Hwy 60 and drove approximately 450 feet down the road before being rear ended by a Nisan Titan pick up truck at a high rate of speed. There was ample time for driver of pickup to have seen our truck and reduced speed as to have not rear ended our bobtail.  The investigation is obviously not complete but it appears that the driver of the pickup was not paying attention.  The pickup struck our bobtail and dislodged the motor fuel tank and ruptured it and also cracked one of the pipe fittings on the piping.  It was a very small crack but it was leaking.  The driver of the vehicle was killed from the impact due to not wearing a seat belt and not from the propane release.  There was never a fire or explosion.  After the scene was clear and we had the bobtail towed back to our yard we flared off the entire cargo tank of product which was 1000 gallons.  This was to reduce pressure on tank and piping so further incident did not occur.
column169: After reviewing the site of the incident it appeared we did everything correctly from a standard operating procedure stand point.  However we can always improve our safety awareness.  I recommended using our hazardous lights when pulling into traffic as another warning to all other motorists that a slow moving truck is entering the highway.  Also I recommended we roll down our window just as a reminder to double check looking for motorists before we enter the roadway.  This will also add another sensory mechanism(hearing) to the equation which will just make every driver more aware.  As far as the packaging is concerned I feel like the truck held up considerably well considering the high rate of speed at impact without a major release of product.

column168: On March 12, 2019 at 2022 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal NKX regarding a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading there was an unknown material released to the trailer floor and the gravel of the terminal yard. Hepaco was dispatched to respond. At 2115 EST, the contractor arrived on site. The contractor tested the material with pH paper and it came out neutral. The contractor then had to get a forklift from their shop to unload the trailer. Hepaco laid out a poly liner on the gravel to place the freight onto. At 0130 EST, the contractor found (1) 55-gal metal drum of UN3082, 9, PGIII "Dowtherm" had released from a pinhole on the bottom seam. It was reported that approximately 1 gallon released to a 15x2 area of the trailer floor. The damaged drum was placed inside (1) 85-gallon metal overpack. The impacted absorbents were placed inside (1) 55-gal metal drum. Both waste containers were staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: On March 15, 2019 at 0725 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal LGT regarding a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 0.5 gallon of UN2922, Corrosive liquids, toxic, n.o.s. (Glycidyl methacrylate), 8(6.1), PGIII released from (1) 55-gallon metal drum due to being punctured by a forklift. The terminal did not have a big enough drum to over pack the damaged 55 gallon drum therefore, ERTS dispatched a contractor. Lonestart Hazmat arrived onsite at 1030 EST. The contractor stated the trailer doors were closed causing the vapor from the material to be trapped in a confined environment, they instructed terminal personnel to stand down from unloading the trailer after taking readings with a gas meter. At 1200 EST, the contractor inspected the drum and determined it had released approximately 0.5 gallon of product. The 55-gallon drum was over-packed into (1) 110-gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: At the original shipper's location, a Veolia employee tilted the poly drum to roll the drum into the truck. At this time, the employee noticed the had creased at the bottom.  When he returned to the Veolia 10 day in transit facility, he immediately notified his supervisor, who determined the best course of action  was to use a drum dolly to unload the drum from the truck while reloading onto another truck for  further transportation.  The Veolia employee placed the drum on the dolly and was moving over the  dock plate to the transfer trailer when he noticed that the drum was leaking.  He placed the drum down on its side to stop the leak and immediately overpacked the leaking drum into a salvage drum.  After  reviewing the incident it was determined that the crease may have caused the drum to fold which  caused an uneven surface at the bottom of the drum.  During the process of going over the dock plate  caused the drum to puncture.
column169: Veolia employees will minimize rolling poly drums to avoid creasing the drums and will use a drum dolly. In the event that the poly drums are located in such a way that use of a drum dolly is not feasible,  Veolia employees will roll the drum to a position where a drum dolly can be used and will slide the  drum dolly to the opposite side of where the drum was rolled on.

column168: On March 13, 2019 at 1950 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal NMP regarding a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 5 gallons of UN3098, Oxidizing liquid, corrosive, n.o.s., 5.1(8), PGII "PAA Sanitizer" released to the trailer floor due to being punctured by a forklift. The terminal requested a contractor be dispatched to respond. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental. At 2310 EST, the contractor arrived on site. The contractor discovered (2) 2.5 gallon plastic jugs that had been punctured by a forklift causing all contents to release being a total of 5 gallons. The contractor re-palatalized the undamaged jugs and shrink-wrapped them back onto the pallet. The release was cleaned up with chem pads and neutralized with sodium metabisulfate. The contractor placed those pads and absorbents into (1) 55-gallon poly drum then tested the impacted area's pH. The impacted trailer floor was successfully neutralized yielding a pH of 6. The contractor instructed the terminal to leave the trailer door open to let it air out. The waste container was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

It was reported that approximately 1 ounce of UN3098, Oxidizing liquid, corrosive, n.o.s., 5.1(8), PGII "PAA Sanitizer" released to the trailer floor while in transit due to being punctured from the freight shifting. The terminal requested that a contractor be dispatched to respond. ERTS dispatched Enviroserve/Sunpro to respond. At 2155 EST, the contractor arrived onsite and began breaking down the pallet to confirm how many containers were damaged. The contractor stated that the pallet was pushed into adjacent cargo while in transit denting some jugs. The contractor then confirmed that (1) 2.5 gallon jug of product was damaged and released 1 ounce of product to the trailer floor. Spill rags and water were used to clean the impacted pallet and trailer floor. The contractor placed the damaged jug as well as impacted spill rags inside (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: On March 15, 2019 at 1615 EST, ERTS was contacted by an XPO Logistics truck driver regarding a cargo release in Parsons, TN. Due to traffic, Hepaco arrived at 2028 EST and located the release at the customer's location. They stated that the tote fell out of the trailer and is currently laying in the street. The contractor estimated 220-gallons of UN1268, Petroleum distillates, n.o.s., 3, PGII "Petroleum Distallates" to the asphalt, soil and creek. The SERC was notified and report number 712 was given by Ron on March 15, 2019 at 1745 EST. The contractor used oil dry to clean the road. The impacted soil was hand scraped and placed into drums. All absorbents and impacted soil were placed inside (3) 55-gallon metal drums. The contractor confirmed the creek was impacted and left boom on site. The contractor also placed bio-bug spray on the bank of the creek. The contractor took the waste drums to XPO Logistics terminal NNA in Nashville, TN. The waste containers were staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: At 1020 ET on March 11, 2019, ERTS received a call from Troy Winthurst from Dohrn regarding a spill that took place on March 8, 2019 inside of a trailer. It was reported that one - 55 gallon drum containing UN2922 "BONDERITE C-AD Deocdzr 16R Aero (TURCO oxidizer 16 REPL)" damaged due to a nail puncture through the drum resulting in the release of at least 15 gallons of material to the trailer floor. The trailer is located at the Dohrn facility in Janesville, WI and requires a response team to overpack the damaged drum and clean the impacted trailer. Reportedly the initial response was performed by Dohrn personnel who secured the drum by rolling the hole to the top to stop the leak. At 1230 ET, HEPACO arrived on site and discovered trailer #055228 filled with impacted debris and the damaged 55 Gallon drum of material. The impacted area appears to stretch 53' x 7' on the trailer floor. There are lines that appear to have the material trailing out of the trailer onto the back of the truck. HEPACO added soda Ash to neutralize the release. The debris was removed, cut up and placed into a drum for disposal. The damaged 55 Gallon Drum was overpacked into a poly overpack. Team staged one - 95 Gallon Poly Overpack containing the damaged 55 Gallon Poly Drum (estimated 3/4 of the way full of material) and one - 55 Gallon Poly Drum containing impacted absorbents, and neutralized material, and PPE were left on site for disposal. The trailer floor had additional soda ash material placed on the floor and recovered the material. HEPACO generated another 5 -55 gallon Poly Drum containing Impacted water from pressure washing the trailer. The trailer floor has been washed and the door of the trailer has been left open to allow the floor to air dry. All waste was containerized for proper disposal.

column168: On 3/12 AA Flight 2738 had AWB 5642 8562 loaded on board.  When the shipment arrived in DFW, the packaging was damaged by water.  Due to regulations, the packaging was compromised, and needed to be repackaged.  During the repacking, the on duty Customer Service Manager (CSM) and the training Crew Chief were escorting the re-packer and when the shipment was opened, a full shipper's declaration, Cargo Aircraft Only labels were attached to the inner box, and the RQ on the label was covered up. These triggers stopped the shipment and in now on hold in AA DFW Cargo.

column168: At approximately 1725 on 3/8/19  Tenerio Davis came to me regarding Pro 086689905 on City Trailer 400810. He reported seeing a liquid under a skid marked as HAZMAT. Tenerio and I exited the trailer after taking pictures of the shipment and pulling information off of the skid.  Upon investigation, it  was discovered the pro was not yet billed, and had incorrect Hazmat classifications on the customer BOL. I approached City dispatch to retrieve the physical BOL since no info could be pulled digitally about the shipment. After getting the information about the shipment,  I called Safety and securit y and spoke with Tyler Shook. After exchanging pictures and documentation with Tyler, he advised me to hold the Trailer in 33 door and wait to hear back from them regarding a spill team being dispatched. ~Spill team has completed their work with the assistance of Ronald Hutchens. A total of 10 five gallon buckets in the shipment were damaged and leaking. The contractor suspects that the pallet was wrapped too tightly and the handles dug into the pails and caused the damage to the pails during transit. The Spill team estimated 8-10 gallons of the liquid ended up on the floor. ~

column168: On March 21, 2019 at 0053 EST ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics XLA regarding a cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading process approximately 1-gallon of an unknown hazardous material released to the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the situation and it was determined a contractor needed to be sent. ERTS dispatched Hepaco with an ETA of 0300. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. Hepaco arrived onsite at 0330 EST, it was determined that one (1) 15-gallon metal drum of UN2290, Isophorone diisocyanate, PGII "DK 190" had been punctured by forklift. Approximately 5-gallons released impacting a 5' x 5' area on the trailer and a 3' x 3' area of asphalt below trailer. Contractor applied granular to both areas. The damaged drum was containerized into one (1) 55 gallon poly drum and the cleanup debris containerized into one (1) 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage

A FRA Inspector found tank car GATX200818 leaking product from the bottom outlet valve and the vapor valve plug less than tool tight.  Upon inspection by a contractor the valve cap was found to be loose.  The vapor valve plug was tightened and the BOV cap was secured.  The car was released for transport.

March 22, 2019 at 2326 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics XCW of one (1) super sack containing UN3085, oxidizing solid, corrosive, n.o.s. (sodium nitrate and sodium hydroxide), 5.1, 8, PGII was torn due to being improperly loaded. Caller stated approximately 10-pounds released onto the tail of the trailer and are unable to cleanup due to not having a container to transfer super sack into. ERTS dispatched Environmental Remediation Services, Inc. to complete cleanup. ERS arrived onsite at 0230 EST and confirmed that approximately 100-pounds of hazardous material has impacted a 10' x 10' area inside trailer due to puncture by forklift. Due to the contamination by forklift blade the remaining material in super sack will be deemed waste. All spilled product and remaining product in the damaged super sack were containerized into two (2) 55-gallon poly drums. Waste remained onsite for the terminal to manage.

During routine facility inspection, facility personnel identified a compromised container. In appropriate personal protective equipment, verified through the internal health and safety department, facility personnel were successful in overpacking the drum into an authorized salvage container for shipment to its final destination. The impact of this release was contained to the warehouse floor and pallet, with no impact to land, soil, water ways or storm drains. The impacted areas were satisfactorily remediated by trained in-house professionals. The container was shipped to its final destination with no further incident.

column168: During routine facility inspections, a release was identified beneath a transport vehicle. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0645 ON 3/22/19 OUR WAREHOUSE AGENT IN HNL DISCOVERED QUESTIONABLE ITEMS ON A SHIPMENT OF CONSTRUCTION MATERIALS AND TOOLS. SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED IN OGG ON 3/21/19 AT APPROXIMATELY 0930 AND TRANSPORTED TO HNL. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION THE FOLLOWING ITEMS WERE DISCOVERED ON 2 OF 4 SKIPS.  1) FIRE EXTINGUISHER (FULLY CHARGED) - UN1044 FIRE EXTINGUISHERS, CLASS 2.2 2) COLD GALVANIZE COATING AEROSOL - UN1950 AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, CLASS 2.1 3) GEOCEL SOLAR PANEL ROOF INSTALLATION SEALANT - UN1263 PAINT, CLASS 3 4) GOOF OFF AEROSOL - SDS SHOWS LAND TRANSPORT ONLY; CALLED MANUFACTURER AND THEY CONFIRMED IT IS HIGHLY FLAMMABLE AND FORBIDDEN BY AIR  SENT EMAIL TO OUR OGG STATION MANAGER ADVISING OF THE SITUATION. SHE IS GATHERING STATEMENTS. SENT EMAIL TO NHL FAA HAZMAT INSPECTORS TO ADVISE THEM AS WELL. INSPECTOR PEARL BELLO ADVISED WE MUST DO A VDRP ALONG WITH THIS REPORT. VDRP FILED ON 3/22/19 BY DIRECTOR OF SAFETY, LORI SAKURAI.
column169: CARRIER:  OGG STATION MANAGER, NOE KALANIKAU, ALREADY ADVISING EMPLOYEES OF SITUATION. SHE IS IN THE PROCESS OF GATHERING STATEMENTS OF AGENTS INVOLVED IN ACCEPTANCE, HANDLING, AND LOADING OF SHIPMENT. EMPLOYEES HAVE ALREADY BEEN ADVISED TO DO RANDOM CHECKS ON SHIPMENTS AND TO BE MORE DILIGENT IN VISUAL INSPECTION OF SHIPMENTS ESPECIALLY SHIPMENTS FROM CONSTRUCTION COMPANIES, MECHANICS WITH THEIR TOOLS & TOOL BOXES, ETC. Waycross, GA - 03/11/2019 - CTCX 732754 - ALCOHOLS, N.O.S. (ETHANOL, GASOLINE)  On 3/11/2019 at 1812, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard discovered CTCX 732754, a loaded tank car of  ALCOHOLS, N.O.S. (ETHANOL, GASOLINE) leaking from the top of the tank car.  The car was isolated and Valero Marketing and Supply Company (Judy Watson, 210-345-3598); Georgia Environmental  Protection Division (report number 89051); NRC (report number 1239831); and CHEMTREC (report  number 2019031100252) were notified. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched  to the scene and found CTCX 732754 leaking from the liquid line valve packing gland nut.  The nut was  tightened.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transportation.

column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGEDTHE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DICK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: On March 23, 2019, at 1348 hours personnel in the CSXT Russell, KY yard reported product leaking from the top of tank car GATX 29297, a load of Styrene Monomer.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Sabic, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2019-0323-00108.  Quick Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched and found the source of the source of the vapor line valve not being fully closed and the secondary securement plug not installed.  Quick Response was able to close the valve and properly secure the closure plug.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper’s representative: Ms. Cindy Whorton.  The car was released for transportation.

column168: At 1118 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal XBO regarding a cargo release. It was reported that there was a release of UN1823, Sodium hydroxide, solid, 8, PGII "Caustic Soda Ash" released from an unknown amount of bags and unknown cause. The terminal requested a contractor be dispatched. At 1320 EST, the contractor arrived on site and confirmed that 1 pound of product released from (1) 20-pound plastic bag due to impacting another skid. The contractor examined all the bags on the skid and found only 1 torn. He placed the damaged bag, released material and impacted shrink wrap inside (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site and staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage. He then re-palatized the remaining bags on the skid to be sent on to the consignee.

column168: On March 28, 2019, at 7:17 EST, XPO terminal (LGT terminal) called ERTS to report at least 8 ounces release from UN1593 "Dichloromethane Mixture" from several 35 kg plastic drums. The caller advised that the release impacted a trailer floor (trailer #313-9565) and the drums were still leaking. The caller also advised that it looked like the release had occurred due to pinhole in the drums which might have occurred due to improper loading of the freight for transport. Following a review of the incident and the reported material involved, ERTS determined that a contractor needs to be sent to the site to conduct the cleanup process. The contractor confirmed that approximately 5 ounces of the product released from (1) 15-gallon plastic drum container due to the container having a pinhole. Only the trailer floor was impacted. They containerized the damaged drum and the used absorbents (ash) into (1) 55-gallon plastic drum.  All generated waste was staged on site..

column14: Corner of FM2517 and US 59 S.
column168: On March 28, 2019 ERTS was contacted regarding damage of two (2) 330 gallon poly totes containing UN308, Environmentally hazardous Substances, liquid, n.o.s. (Alkylbenzenesulfonate), MARINE POLLUTANT,9, PGIII that were punctured due to tractor trailer roll-over. The Trailer containing load was staged at a salvage yard located at 511 East Sabine Street Carthage, Texas 75633. No release of material occurred, contractor transferred contents of each tote into DOT shippable poly totes and shipped to destination. Contractor cut apart the two (2) damaged totes and placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal open top drum and one (1) 55-gallon open top poly drum. Drums were transported to XPO terminal LXO located at 1235 Gazin St., Houston, TX 77020 and staged in OS&D for terminal to manage.        3/23/19 at 0200 EST XPO experienced a tractor trailer rolled over. ERST was not notified of this accident. The trailer is currently at the salvage yard (511 East Sabine Street  Carthage, Texas 75633) and It was discovered a steel beam going thru a tote containing "Poly Step LAS-40" there has been no release but salvage yard personnel requested to have a team sent to site to assist due to steel beam puncturing the tote it will release some product once removed for transfer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the contractor. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. There is no regulatory reporting required for this release due to spills in trailers and contained areas not being reportable.  Waste container entry is provided below. SDS is uploaded to entry; status set to waste label provided. Contractor dispatched from Lonestar with an ETA of 1 hr and 15 minutes. ERTS will upload the BOL and SDS. A DOT5800 will be required for this incident due to the size of the tote.

column168: On March 30, 2019 at 0320, XPO Logistics terminal USA experienced an approximate 25-pound release of UN3378, sodium carbonate peroxyhydrate, 5.1, PG II "GreenClean Pro" from one (1) 50-pound bag. It was discovered the bag had been torn due to nail on the skid, all material contained to trailer floor. After reviewing the SDS the XPO personnel advised they had the proper PPE and containers to clean released material. The recovered material and damaged bag were containerized into one (1) 5-gallon plastic container and staged in OS&D for XPO to manage for disposal. No drains, soils or waterways impacted by this release.

On 03-11-2019, FRA Inspector in the  CSXT Collier Yard, Petersburg VA, discovered SBLX24062, a loaded  tank car of  Sodium Hydroxide Solution, with dried produce under the manway and on the side of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper “Olin Corp” was  notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2019-0311-00238). Hepaco,  a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found two loose manway bolts. The issue was identified and corrective actions were made. Contractor personnel also cleaned the dried product off the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not  require a special switching move.  NO   7.1 required  Cause Code: 200 NARRI: 100

column168: During loading, freight was struck with equipment, causing damage. Damage caused a release of product. Contractor recovered released product with absorbents and placed into a container for proper disposal.
column169: Provide additional training to material handlers to ensure that they are implementing proper freight handling techniques and are able to recognize and prevent potential future incidents.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: Tank farm operator was loading an outbound tanker with 20% Caustic Soda solution. The tanker was smaller than required and resulted in an approximate 100 gallon overfill. Contributing factors included not using a loading checklist/form and differences in product densities between 20% and 20% caustic soda products.  Mass (lbs) is entered into the controller for the loading unit not volume (gallons). The tanker and released product were inside containment. There were no injuries.
column169: Corrective actions included listing tanker volumes on internal spreadsheet listing last contained information for our tankers.  Tanker volumes were also placed at the tanker loading area to help employees understand tanker capacities.  Tanker loading checklist/form is also being implemented at this facility.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A saturated 14 gallon fiber drum was discovered on a vehicle while being offloaded at the Veolia  transfer facility.  The 14 gallon fiber drum was saturated about 40% up the drum but no hazardous materials were released beyond the 14 gallon fiber drum.  Inside of the drum were 4 x 1 gallon glass bottles containing hydrochloric acid solution, triethylamine, aresenate, acetic acid solution (10-50% in  water), glycine, and sodium hydroxide solution.  It appears the contents of the glass inner containers froze due to the cold outside temperatures.  When the contents froze it may have cracked the glass  inner containers which resulted in the spill when the temperatures were no longer freezing.  There was approximately 1 pint of hazardous material that was released from the inner glass containers.  The  spilled material was absorbed by the absorbent material packed inside the outer packaging but the outside of the 14 gallon fiber was dampened by the release.  The 14 gallon container was bagged and overpacked to  prevent further release while in transportation.
column169: To help prevent a recurrence, the hazard of freezing temperatures causing containers to break has been shared with the employees.

column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH WEST ON STH 37, STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION AT CTH B, WAITED FOR TRAFFIC TO CLEAR, THEN BEGAN A LEFT TURN ONTO CTH B. WHILE MAKING THE LEFT TURN, THE VEHICLE ENCOUNTERED AN AREA OF BLACK ICE. VEHICLE BEGAN TO SLIDE, THEN ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. DURING THE ROLL, A LIQUID PROPANE COOLANT LINE BROKE AT THE POINT WHERE IT CONNECTS TO A "T" IN THE LIQUID LINE AT THE REAR OF THE 3499 GALLON LP TANK. THE LIQUID LINE, QUARTER TURN, SHUT OFF VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION BUT A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR CONTINUED TO LEAK PAST THE VALVE CREATING AN LEL BETWEEN 0 AND 54%. THE LEAK WAS MITIGATED WHEN THE LIQUID PROPANE WAS PUMPED COMPLETELY FROM THE TANK AND THE REMAINING VAPOR WAS FLARED AND THE PROPANE TANK WAS EMPTY.

03/30/19, at 22:09 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk yard discovered GATX79928, a loaded tank car of Methanol, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and International-Matex Tank Terminal, Selkirk Fire Department NYS DEC , NYS DOT and NRC were notified.  (2019-03-03-000102. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon cutting the security seal and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the primary valve to fittings plate flange on the liquid education line was leaking from the flange bolt area. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Mario Lamanno 201-852-1532. Contractor personnel secured the leak by tightening the flange securement bolts. The leak was secured and the car placed on hazmat hold until shipper can arrange for repairs to railcar. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

column168: ON 03/11/2019 AT APPROXIMATELY 0020 HOURS, A YARD CREW REPORTED AN ODOR EMANATING FROM TANK CARS LOCATED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) KNOCHE YARD IN KANSAS CITY, MO. A RESPONDER FROM THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED TO THE YARD. A RAILROAD QUALIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO MOBILIZED TO ASSIST WITH INVESTIGATING THE ODOR AND TO SECURE ANY IDENTIFIED DEFECTS.  DURING THE INITIAL INVESTIGATION, THE YARD PERIMETER, AT GROUND LEVEL. PRESENTED NO ODOR AND NON-DETECT READINGS ON AIR MONITORING DEVICES (USING TWO METERS). MULTIPLE CARS WERE INSPECTED AT GROUND LEVEL WITH NO ODOR OR AIR METER DETECTION. THEN, SUSPECT CARS WERE ASCENDED AND INSPECTED FROM THE TOP. DURING THESE INSPECTIONS, UTLX 956094 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING (DETECTED WITH AIR MONITORING METER, AUDIBLE HISS NOISE, AND SLIGHT ODOR). THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM A LOOSE SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG ON THE B AND LIQUID VALVE. THE B END LIQUID VALVE. THE B END LIQUID VALVE WAS FOUND IN A SLIGHTLY OPEN POSITION. THE LOOSE CLOSURES WERE SECURED. PRIOR TO RELEASING THE CAR BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION, ALL OTHER CLOSURES WERE VERIFIED AS SECURE.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THE CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FEELINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: On breakdown of ULD PMC92456DL, received at LHR EX DL010/19-20MAR a number of packages of air waybill 006 60651986 were externally contaminated with a wet oily liquid, further traces of the liquid were on the base of the ULD.  5 pieces of consignment diesel engine powered machinery, under air waybill 006 09457840 had also been loaded on the ULD and appeared to have leaked the oily fluid from one or two of the pieces loaded on the PMC.  On investigation of the air waybill and DGD it became apparent that the shipment had been flown with an incorrectly completed DGD. The proper shipping name used was Engine, Internal Combustion, Flammable Liquid Powered, when it should have been Machinery, Flammable Liquid powered.  In addition the type of packaging stated on the DGD was wooden crates. As per Appendix A of IATA DG regs “Crates are not acceptable as packagings in Air transport except as an Overpack”     Subsequent FAA Inspection Detail>: A shipper inspection was conducted at Cummins Power Generation on March 27, 2019. The information on the leaking fluid indicated that it was not regulated as dangerous goods (see attached).   The inspector assigned verified that the company’s training records, SDS, two year file of shipping papers, marking, labeling and packaging all were in compliance. No violations were noted.

column168: TRUCK SC-5012 WAS STAGED IN THE 10-DAY YARD LATE ON 03-26-19. IN REVIEW OF THE DRIVER POST TRIP INSPECTION THE TRUCK IS DOT COMPLIANT, AND NO LEAKS ARE NOTED. THE WASTE IS MANIFESTED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID NOS (LEAD) WITH A RCRA CODE OF D008. ON THE MORNING OF 03-27-19, THE DRIVER WAS GOING TO TRANSPORT THE TRUCK SC-5012 TO CLEAN EARTH OF NORTH JERSEY FOR DISPOSAL. HE NOTICED A DRIP FROM THE REAR DOOR DURING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION, PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP, AND CALLED DISPATCH AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM. AT THAT TIME THE PUDDLE WAS LESS THAN 2 FEET IN DIAMETER. DISPATCH DIRECTED B.POWELL AND N. ZAMBRANO TO USE ANOTHER TRUCK, PV-4130, TO TRANSFER THE LOAD. PV-4130 HAS EXACTLY THE SAME TYPE OF WASTE IN IT FROM THE SAME GENERATOR. AS THEY WERE TRANSFERRING THE LOAD, A SMALL SECTION OF WELD, ON THE TOP FRONT OF THE TANK ON SC-5012 STARTED TO ALSO LEAK. IT WAS A VERY SMALL LEAK FROM PIN HOLES IN ABOUT 3" OF THE WELD. ONE OF THE DRIVERS PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE TRUCK TO CATCH THE DRIPS. THE TEAM CONTINUED TO TRANSFER THE LOAD TO ALLEVIATE BOTH LEAKS.  AT ABOUT 10:30 AM NICK PREVOSTI AND MAUREEN TROESCHER, ACV ENVIRO-EH&S MANAGERS, WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. THEY CONFIRMED THE LEAKS AND EXTENT OF THE SPILL WERE CONTAINED. THERE WAS LESS THAN 50 GALLONS OF LIQUID IN THE VICINITY OF THE TRUCK, AND THE YARD SUPERVISOR HAD ALREADY PLACED A SPEEDI DRY BERM AROUND THE PUDDLES, NJDEP WAS NOTIFIED AT AROUND 12:00PM - INCIDENT # 19-03-27-1241-32.  THE DRIP FROM THE BACK OF SC-5012 STOPPED BEFORE ALL THE MATERIAL WAS REMOVED. APPARENTLY, THE WEIGHT OF THE LOAD WAS CAUSING THE REAR DOOR LEAK. THE LOAD WAS LOWERED ENOUGH SO THAT WASTE WAS FAR BELOW THE CRACKED WELD. ALL MATERIAL WAS VACUUMED BACK INTO SC-5012. ANY WASTE ON THE ACTUAL VEHICLE WAS WIPED OFF THE EXTERIOR AND THOSE PADS WERE ALSO VACUUMED BACK INTO THE TRUCK. SC-5012 HAD NO LEAKS AT THIS POINT. BOTH TRUCKS WERE SENT TO CLEAN EARTH FOR DISPOSAL. THE VEHICLE IS CURRENTLY OUT OF SERVICE FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. ONCE AT THE FACILITY BASED ON STANDARD PROCEDURE FOR HANDLING THIS CUSTOMER WASTE, A TCLP ANALYSIS WAS COMPLETED AND IT WAS CONFIRMED THAT THE MATERIALS WAS NON-HAZARDOUS WITH LEAD FAR BELOW RCRA CHARACTERISTIC LEVEL.
column169: PROPER SPILL PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED ONCE SPILL WAS IDENTIFIED. AS MENTIONED ABOVE, PAILS WERE PLACED UNDER THE DRIPS AND SPEEDI DRY WAS POURED AROUND ANY PUDDLES TO ENSURE CONTAINMENT. THE LEAKS ON SC-5012 WERE ALLEVIATED BY TRANSFERRING SOME OF THE MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER TRUCK WITH THE SAME WASTE FROM SAME GENERATOR. SC-5012 WILL HAVE ALL WELDS CHECKED AND GASKET REPLACED. THE HYDRAULICS THAT HOLD THE REAR DOOR WILL ALSO BE CHECKED.

column169: WE DON'T KNOW HOW IT HAPPENED OR HOW TO PREVENT YET. WE HAVE TALKED TO THE FIRE CHIEF, ATF, FMCSA, PHMSA. THEY STILL DON'T UNDERSTAND HOW IT HAPPENED AND SAY IT SHOULD NOT HAVE EXPLODED. THREE MEMBERS OF PHSMA VISITED US ON 4-10-19 AND LOOKED AT SIMILAR TRAILER TRYING TO FIGURE OUT A THEORY. THERE NAMES: DWIGHT MECKFESSEL, SEAN E LYNUM, AND KEIRAN STEWART. THEY SAID THEY WOULD SEND US A REPORT WHEN THEIR INVESTIGATION IS COMPLETE.  *ATTACHED POLICE REPORT + FIRE REPORT + ADDITIONAL DESCRIPTION PAGE*

column168: On 3/22/19 at approximately 02:00, BNSF carmen observed the TCIX 21093 venting from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and Hazmat responders notified to inspect the car.  Upon inspection, BNSF Hazmat responders noted the vapors to be coming from the Salco Tri-vent rupture disk assembly.  Inspection through the inspection port showed that the rupture disk was intact and in place, however HCl vapor was escaping around the disk.  A contractor was dispatched with a replacement rupture disk to assist with replacement and further inspection.  When removed, the disk was found to have partially delaminated the gasket and thus not providing an adequate seal.  A new rupture disk was installed and the car was decontaminated and allowed to continue in transportation.
column169: Rupture disks should be regularly inspected and replaced as part of a standard procedure.  Shippers should inspect and have a replacement plan in place for rupture disks.  It is not known when this disk was last replaced.(NAR:439)

column168: Tank car TILX 281807 arrived in BNSF yard at Glendive, MT with obvious signs of leakage from the protective housing on the top of the car.  Pinnacle Engineering was dispatched to investigate and correct.  Upon arrival, Pinnacle responders found the liquid valve partially opened and secondary closure plug loose.  Closed valve, properly tightened plug, no additional release.  Remediation and cleanup was confined to the car.  Once cleanup and securement was completed, car was released into service.
column169: Train and audit for compliance to ensure loading personnel are properly securing DOT hazmat packages per established regulations.(NAR:119)

column168: On 3/5/19 received notification from Hub personnel at the BNSF Los Angeles, CA     IMF, that unit JBHU 308300 was found leaking a white substance from underneath the container floor, spilling less than 5 ounces of product on the ground. Waybill list this shipment as containing multiple hazardous shipments, this unit was moved to containment pit area pending interior inspection of the cargo. Interior inspection of the cargo conducted by United Pumping Services revealed a single layer of mix palletized freight, that was stowed two rows wide throughout the container, this shipment was secured with two plys of ty   guard at the rear of the load. Responder identified a damaged IBC tote filled with "Fabra Kleen," a cleaning solution classified as a class 8 corrosive hazardous substance UN1824. The damaged tote had two cracks found on the top of the container, causing product to slosh back loosing approximately 20 gallons of product. The surrounding freight became contaminated and the container floor was saturated with the spilled product. Responders with United Pumping Services successfully transferred the product from the damaged IBC tote into a good order IBC tote and has remediated the contaminated freight and container floor. This shipment has been released for out   gate at the drivers discretion.
column169: Ensure cargo packages are not damaged during loading and secure adjacent packages to prevent contact and damage during transportation.(NAR:655)

ACCORDING TO SDS SECTION 14 THE PACKAGE SHOULD HAVE HAD A #8 CORROSIVE LABEL.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: Seventeen (17) Company Fire Extinguishers weighing 416 pounds from the Airlines' Nome, Alaska passenger terminal were expired and needed to be transported to Company Headquarters for retesting and re-certification.   Company employees (Aircraft Mechanics) prepared the shipment to travel on two "cargo aircraft only" non-revenue, re-position flights to return the expired extinguishers to Company Headquarters.   Nome employees instructed the pilots of the first aircraft to deliver the extinguishers to Unalakleet, Alaska, a hub airport, for transfer to a Company cargo aircraft that was expected later that day.   Because the flights were on non-revenue re-position flight, employees completed cargo manifests but failed to follow company procedures on Hazmat acceptance. Subsequently, hazmat paperwork and PIC notification forms were not created for the shipment.   The extinguishers were flown to Unalakleet on 3-20-19 as COMAT.   The expected Company freighter aircraft never arrived at Unalakleet due to aircraft maintenance issues and the extinguishers were stored in the Cargo building overnight.   The next day, a Company revenue passenger flight operated into Unalakleet. Ramp agents at the Unalakleet station loaded the extinguishers onto the aircraft as COMAT. Because the shipment did not have hazmat paperwork and associated PIC notification paperwork, the units were loaded onto the aircraft and assumed to not be hazmat.   The aircraft flew without incident to Anchorage, Alaska on 3-21-19.  Cargo Agents offloading the aircraft identified the Fire Extinguishers as improperly shipped hazmat and reported the improperly documented shipment to the company.   The company filed a Voluntary Disclosure Report with the FAA.
column169: The Company found the root cause of this event to be the shipping employees failure to follow HAZMAT shipping protocol due to the first flight being a non-revenue, re-position flight. The corrective action determined by our Company was to require all shipments to follow Cargo acceptance procedures regardless whether the flight is non-revenue re-position or passenger carrying.   The Company Director of Airports reviewed the violations and the requirements to comply with HAZMAT shipping procedures with the Unalakleet and Nome Airport managers immediately after becoming aware of the incident. (3-27-19)  The Company Director of Aircraft Maintenance mandated that his mechanics can no longer initiate and or accept shipments on non-revenue flights and that all shipments must be initiated by trained Company Cargo Agents in accordance with Company cargo and hazmat acceptance and loading policies.  Memo sent out 4-11-19.   The Director of Airports has mandated all Unalakleet ground agents and Nome to complete remedial Hazmat Recognition training no later than 5-10-19. The Director of Airports is also training 2 more ramp agents in Hazmat acceptance to increase the knowledge of their group.

column168: DRIVER COMPLETED LOADING HIS TRAILER WITH 18% REGENERATED HYDROCHLORIC ACID, CLOSED THE DOME LID AND COMPLETED HIS POST TRIP CHECKLIST INCLUDING A SLOSH TEST AND PULLED HIS UNIT AROUND NEXT TRUCK TO PULL IN. HE COMPLETED HIS PAPER, REDID THE SLOSH TEST AND PULLED OUT TO DELIVER HIS LOAD. HE TRAVELED ABOUT 1/2/ MILE TO THE PLANT GATE, TROUGH THE GUARD AGTE AND OVER A BRIDGE TO A STOP LIGHT WHEN ANOTHER DRIVER NOTIFIED HIM HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING. HE PULLED OVER TO THE SHOULDER AND FOUND THE DOME BOLTS WERE LOOSE. HE TIGHTENED UP THE BOLTS, NOTIFIED SUPERVISION AND RETURNED TO THE YARD TO HAVE HIS TRAILER CHECKED FOR ANY GASKET OR MECHANICAL ISSUES WITH THE DOME. NONE WERE FOUND.  NO LEAKAGE OCCURRED UNTIL THE DRIVER REACHED THE GUARD GATE, AT THE FOOT OF THE BRIDGE AND AT THE LIGHT. THE CONCLUSION IS THE DOME WAS CLOSED BUT NOT SECURED PROPERLY TO PREVENT LEAKAGE.  THE DRIVER FOLLOWED THE LEAK PREVENTION CHECK LIST BUT FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE DOME BOLTS SINCE THEY WERE LOSE AFTER HE STOPPED OUTSIDE THE PLANT.  THE 40 GALLONS SPILLED WERE NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP BY PLANT PERSONNEL AT THE LOCATIONS MENTIONED.
column169: THE INCIDENT WILL BE PUBLICIZED TO ALL DRIVERS. THE LEAK PREVENTION CHECKLIST HAS BEEN MODIFIED TO INCLUDE RECHECKING THE DOME LID BOLTS FOR TIGHTNESS. THE DRIVERS WILL RETRAINED ON THE REVISED CHECKLIST TO INSURE ON DOME LID ARE SECURED PROPERLY.

column168: THE ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER FUEL OIL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. THE DRIVER FAILED TO OPEN A VALVE ON THE STORAGE TANK LOADING LINE PRIOR TO INITIATING THE DELIVERY. THIS CAUSED THE PRESSURE TO BUILD IN THE LINE AND THE VALVE TO RUPTURE. THE YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: THE KA BULK TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, IT APPEARS THAT THE STORAGE OVER-PRESSURIZED. THIS CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL TO BE RELEASED. ENVIROSERVE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KA BULK TRANSPORT, LLC HAS NOTIFIED THE CUSTOMER OF THE POTENTIAL VENTING ISSUES WITH THEIR STORAGE TANK SO PROPER REPAIRS CAN BE MADE.

column168: During routine facility operations, facility personnel identified a compromised container resulting in a small release of its contents. In appropriate personal protective equipment, personnel were successful in overpacking the compromised container and remediation of the trailer floor. This release was contained to the transport trailer floor with no impact to land, soil, water ways or storm drains. The container was sent to its final destination without further incident.
column169: An internal investigation was initiated and the parties involved in the staging of the transport trailer were all thoroughly retrained on proper load securement techniques and requirements.

column168: On 03/26/19 at 1913 an unknown amount of product "UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide, Solution 8 PG II" was discovered leaking from at least one tote. 2215 EST, confirms there are no drains or waterways impacted by the release, most of the trailer floor is impacted as well as asphalt and soil. There is a 120' trail on the asphalt/gravel shoulder and then it turns and crosses approximately 25' of grass and pools in a roadside soil ditch. The tote is found to have a puncture approximately the size of a quarter caused by a possible abrasion; however, there were no nails or other protrusions found in the trailer.  Approximately, 110 gallons remain in the damaged tote. All of the other totes are filled to 330-gallon capacity. It's estimated that approximately 20 gallons of material remained in the trailer and 200 gallons have released to the environment.  A total of four 55 gallon poly drums of clean product were created from emptying the damaged tote and were taken for disposal. On 04/01/2019, Contractor reported to ERTS that the site was marking Hotter than anticipated and that they ended up with 6 roll of boxes of impacted soil from the site and that the back fill was estimated at 92 tons of clean soil The Required Geologist was on site and mapping the area as well as taking samples during the entire excavation and has marked the site clean at this time.

column168: On 3/6/19 at approximately 1630 hours an IMTT Chemical Operator contacted to Chemical Supervisors over to rack W10/W11 because of an over loaded Furfuryl Alcohol truck. Upon arrival the supervisors noticed Furfuryl Alcohol running down the side of the truck. When they got to the rack they observed the crash box of the truck was filled with product and there was also product coming down the vapor stack due to the product filling up the vapor line. The vapor line, product line, and high level lance were packed with ^ product. The two Supervisors and the Operator carefully drained both hoses so they could be removed without any issues. After everything was disconnected and secured US Ecology(IMTT's OSRO) cleaned up the ground and the side of the truck was rinsed off.
column169: IMTT conducted a thorough investigation and determined that the high level on the lance(loading . connection) never went offto shut down the load which caused the truck to overflow. This system was taken out of service, repaired, re-tested and placed back into service.

column168: ON MARCH 4, 2019 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:15 AM A DESULFURIZATION TANKER SCHEDULED TO BE SHIPPED TO ESM, KINGSBURY, WAS DAMAGED WHEN THE DRIVER MISSED THE KINGPIN WHILE ATTEMPTING TO CONNECT TO TANKER AND STRUCK THE FRONT DISCHARGE HOPPER. A 6 TO 8 INCH PIECE OF STEEL, ONE INCH IN DIAMETER HAD BEEN WELDED TO THE REAR BUMPER OF THE TRUCK AND PIERCED THE HOPPER ON IMPACT RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF 1500 POUNDS OF PRODUCT. THIS PRODUCT IS A SOLID MATERIAL CONSISTING OF 60% CALCIUM CARBIDE, 36.5% LIME, AND 2.5% GILSONITE. A 911 CALL WAS PLACED NOTIFYING LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WHILE PLANT PERSONNEL QUICKLY PLUGGED THE PUNCTURE, STOPPING FURTHER RELEASE OF MATERIAL. OTHER NEARBY TRAILERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AREA.  COMPANY REPRESENTATIVES MET WITH THE LOCAL FIRST RESPONDERS TO ESTABLISH A PLAN OF ACTION. SUBURBAN TOWING WAS CALLED TO MOVE THE DAMAGED TANK AWAY FROM THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THE TEMPORARY PLUG WAS REINFORCED AND THE TANKER MOVED INDOORS FOR OFFLOADING AND PERMANENT REPAIR. A BERM O SAND WAS PLACED AROUND THE SPILLED PRODUCT TO MITIGATE POTENTIAL RUNOFF IN THE EVENT OF RAIN. THE AREA WAS CORDONED OFF AND THE MATERIAL ALLOWED TO NATURALLY SLAKE OUT. ALL RESIDUAL MATERIAL WILL BE COLLECTED AND USED IN OUR CALCIUM HYDROXIDE PROCESS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, SUSTAINED EQUIPMENT DAMAGE, OR SUBSEQUENT RELEASES AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT AND NO FURTHER IMPACT FROM THIS EVENT ARE ANTICIPATED.
column169: THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT IS EMPLOYED BY THE CUSTOMER AND THE TANKER IS OWNED BY THE CUSTOMER. THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT, INCLUDING ALL FINDINGS IN THIS CASE. CARBIDE INDUSTRIES HAS MADE RECOMMENDATIONS TO THE CUSTOMER CONCERNING POSSIBLE MODIFICATION TO THIS TYPE OF TANKER AND THE REMOVAL OF THE BUMPER MOUNTED PIECE OF STEEL FROM THE TRACTOR TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS NATURE.

column168: AFTER LOADING AND SECURING WASTE ON THE TRAILER THE DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE THE DRUM DOLLY. AT SOME POINT DURING TRANSIT THE DRUM DOLLY SHIFTED AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE NEXT STOP THE DRIVER NOTICED THE SPILL HAD OCCURRED. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR (MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL) WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL. IT APPEARS THAT THE SPILL WAS LIMITED TO THE CUSTOMER'S PROPERLY AND THE ROADWAY JUST OUTSIDE THEIR DRIVEWAY. CLEANUP OPERATIONS WERE FROM APPROXIMATELY 17:00 - 19:15.  THERE ARE NO PHOTOS OF THE PUNCTURED DRUM.
column169: TRAINING HAS BEEN CONDUCTED WITH ALL DRIVERS EMPHASIZING THE IMPORTANCE OF SECURING ALL DRUMS, EQUIPMENT AND ANYTHING ELSE DURING TRANSIT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column168: Original comments:  Package was found during the outbound pm shift with no notes attached or left behind for remarks or comments. Box was found at QA in the damage section with its box soaking in lactic acid. The contents labels were faded away. The screw on cap was crushed inward possibly from being dropped or crushed under another package.  New Comments: Package probably damaged during transit. No information left behind by previous shift of what occurred to the package.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, PALED AND SPLIT TO THE SOUTH SORT AISLE. THERE THE PACKAGE WAS SORTED INTO THE BOX-LINE. WHEN IT GOT TO THE PRE-LOADER HE NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE CORNER OF THE BOX. HE STOPPED FORWARD MOVEMENT, LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. HE THEN CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER, FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET PLACE THE PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TUB. THE EQUIPMENT WAS DECONTAMINATED FOLLOWING THE EQUIPMENT DECONTAMINATION CHECK LIST. THE RESPONDER BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. IT WAS THERE, IT WAS DISCOVERED TO CONTAIN AN AEROSOL CAN.

column168: MIKE ANCONA (EMPL) WAS WORKING TRAILER 53647 AND PULLED OFF LEAKING DRUM GOT WAS NOT AWARE IT WAS OR HAD BEEN LEAKING. HE SAID THE SMELL WAS VERY FAINT AND GOT WORSE AS HE KEPT WORKING. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS WET THROUGH A MAJORITY OF THE TRAILER. DAN VALDEZ (EMP 2) CAME IN TO HELP AND NOTICED THE SMELL. HE WAS ALSO TOLD BY EMPL THAT HE WAS FEELING SICK BECAUSE OF SMELL. THEY STARTED TO WORK AGAIN AND REACH SEE (EMP 5) CAME IN. ABOUT 20 MIN AFTER EMP 2. EMP 3 CALLED ME (BRIAN MORRIS) AND REPORTED ALL OF THE ABOVE. WE EVACUATED FACILITY AND CALLED SAFETY. SAFETY ADVISED TO CALL 911 AND FIRE DEPARTMENT SHOWED UP.
column169: - COMPLETE FAILURE NOT KNOWN BUT WOULD APPEAR TO BE PINCHED BY OTHER FREIGHTER HIT WITH FORK LIFT.  - BETTER INSPECTION OF WHERE FLUIDS CAME FROM WOULD HAVE MITIGATED THE SPILL AREA & AMOUNT.

column168: RESPONDER CALLED TO SILVER BELT FOR LEAKING PACKAGE. RESPONDED WITH FULL PPE, DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET. PACKAGE WAS OPEN ON SIDE AND 2 AEROSOL CANS WITH BROKEN TOPS WERE NEXT TO PACKAGE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS TO INDICATE CONTENTS. RESPONDER PLACED PACKAGE AND 2 AEROSOLS IN SPILL TUB AND RETURNED TO DMP FOR PROCESSING. LIQUID FROM AEROSOLS CONTAINED TO PACKAGE. CARTON APPEARS TO BE REUSED.

column168: WSOR NON-REPORTABLE ETHANOL LEAK (BARDELL, WII): ON MARCH 31ST AT APPROXIMATELY 15:28 WE CONTACTED BY AN FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR STATING AN ETHANOL TANK (UTLX 299081) ON THE FOX LAKE SUB IN THE NORTH PASS AT BARDWELL WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE CAP. THE FRA INSPECTOR STATED IT WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF 15-20 DROPLETS A MINUTE. SENIOR TRAIN MASTER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE WHERE HE PLACED A CATCH BUCKET UNDERNEATH THE LEAK AND NOTED THE CAR LEAK HAD SLOWED TO 1 DROPLET EVERY 30-45 SECONDS. CUSTOMER AT BADGER STATE ETHANOL HAS BEEN NOTIFIED AND SENDING A REPAIR TEAM. IF THE CAR IS UNABLE TO BE REPAIRED THE BSE TEAM WILL TRANS-LOAD THE CAR AND WE WILL SEND THE CAR HOME SHOP FOR REPAIR. OUR ENVIRONMENTAL TEAM IS AWARE AND THE SITUATION IS NON-RE-PORTABLE AT THIS TIME.
column169: CUSTOMER IS AWARE OF THE ISSUE THAT AROSE AND WILL CHANGE PROCESS AS NEEDED.

SAND WAS PUT DOWN TO DAM A CATCH BASIN AND A CATCH PAN WAS PUT BELOW THE HATCH TO CATCH THE FALLING OIL AND VACUUMED INTO THE VAC TRUCKS. THEY THEN DRILLED INTO THE TANKER TO PUMP OUT THE ENTIRE LOAD INTO THEIR TRUCKS. THE DRIVER WAS UNHURT IN THE ACCIDENT.
column169: WE HIRE ONLY SKILLED DRIVERS WITH MINIMUM OF A YEARS EXPERIENCE. THIS WAS AN UNFORTUNATE ACCIDENT AND THE FIRST OF OUR KIND IN 40 YEARS OF DOING BUSINESS. DRIVER WAS ACQUIRED FROM PURCHASE OF ANOTHER COMPANY AND AN ARMY VETERAN THAT WE GAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO KEEP HIS POSITION BASED ON HIS EXPERIENCE. HE WAS ON HIS SAME DAILY ROUTE THAT HE DELIVERED ON FOR THE PAST 8 MONTHS AND UNFORTUNATELY MADE A TERRIBLE MISTAKE. WE WILL CONTINUE TO PROVIDE THE BEST TRAINING FOR OUR DRIVERS TO ENSURE THE SAFETY OF THE PUBLIC. WE CONDUCT AUTOMATIC SAFETY INSPECTIONS TO KEEP ALL OF OUR EQUIPMENT SAFE FOR THE ROADS. WE TAKE PRIDE IN BEING THE BIGGEST WATER AND HEATING OIL CARRIERS IN THE STATE.

column168: THE ACCIDENT/ROLLOVER OCCURRED ON MARCH 10, 2019 @ 09:45 DURING WINTER CONDITIONS THE ROAD WAS CLEAR OF SNOW, BUT ICY. THE TRUCK/TRAILER COMBINATION WAS TRAVELING @ OR UNDER THE POSTED SPEED LIMIT DOWN A GRADE WHICH SWEPT INTO A LEFT CURVE. THE TRACTOR BROKE FREE OF TRACTION SLIDING OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD HITTING A CULVERT. THIS CAUSED THE TRACTOR FRAME TO BUCKLE CAUSING THE TRAILER TO ROLL OVER COMPLETELY STRIKING A UTILITY POLE. THE UNIT SLIDE FURTHER UP THE ROADWAY A LONG DISTANCE STRIKING A SECOND UTILITY POLE, THEN HITTING A PARKED CAR PUSHING THAT CAR INTO A THIRD UTILITY POLE COMING TO A STOP.  OUR DRIVER CALLED 911 AND THE COMPANY TO INFORM OF WHAT HAPPENED. EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH (2) EMERGENCY SPILL COMPANIES, TWO TOW SERVICES ALONG WITH A HOST OF EMERGENCY RESPONDERS. THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE IS ESTIMATED AT 1 HOUR WHEN THE TRAILER WAS AIR DRILLED TO RECOVER ANY PETROLEUM REMAINING WHICH WAS APPROX. 1200 GALS. THE CARGO TANK WAS BREECHED IN (4) LOCATIONS FROM A (1) 4" SCRUB THROUGH BREECH FROM BLACKTOP, (1) 3" PUNCTURE FROM A ROAD SIGN AND (2) TEARS FROM THE DAMAGE TO THE OUTER SHELL.  TWO EMERGENCY SPILL RESPONSE COMPANIES WORKED TO CONTROL/CAPTURE THE RELEASE, BUT THE PETROLEUM FLOWED THROUGH TWO PROPERTIES IMPACTING SOIL AND WET LAND. EXCAVATORS, VAC TRUCKS, SPILL BOOMS INCLUDING OCEAN BOOM FOR THE WATERWAYS. MONITORING OF THE WETLANDS OCCURRED THROUGH OUT THE REMEDIATION PHASES. ALL AGENCIES INCLUDING THE NY DEC, ORANGE COUNTY HAZMAT AND THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH WERE INVOLVED.
column169: WE HAVE DONE A REVIEW OF OUR TRAINING POLICIES. WE HAVE SHARED THE INFORMATION FORM THE EVENT WITH ALL THE EMPLOYEES AS AWARENESS TRAINING. WE HAVE HAD INTERNAL DISCUSSIONS FOR IMPROVEMENTS IF NEEDED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Driver looked in sight glass and thought the diesel compartment was empty so he closed the external valve and popped both ears resulting in diesel to spray out. This startled the driver causing him to drop the unload hose resulting in approximately 30gal of diesel to run out on the concrete. The driver then hooked the hose back up to the compartment and placed his absorbent pads to contain the spill and then called the Topeka Fire Dept. The Fire Dept. placed "Floor Dry" on the spill and then swept most of it down to the street for the Street Sweeper to remove. The remaining Floor Dry was swept up by the driver and placed in a trash bag along with the absorbent pads, which were placed in the GTI tractor. The absorbent boom socks were loaded onto the GTI hose rack to be hauled back to the yard.
